Starbucks Capstone Challenge¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains simulated data that mimics customer behavior on the Starbucks rewards mobile app. Once every few days, Starbucks sends out an offer to users of the mobile app. An offer can be merely an advertisement for a drink or an actual offer such as a discount or BOGO (buy one get one free). Some users might not receive any offer during certain weeks.

Not all users receive the same offer, and that is the challenge to solve with this data set.

Your task is to combine transaction, demographic and offer data to determine which demographic groups respond best to which offer type. This data set is a simplified version of the real Starbucks app because the underlying simulator only has one product whereas Starbucks actually sells dozens of products.

Every offer has a validity period before the offer expires. As an example, a BOGO offer might be valid for only 5 days. You'll see in the data set that informational offers have a validity period even though these ads are merely providing information about a product; for example, if an informational offer has 7 days of validity, you can assume the customer is feeling the influence of the offer for 7 days after receiving the advertisement.

You'll be given transactional data showing user purchases made on the app including the timestamp of purchase and the amount of money spent on a purchase. This transactional data also has a record for each offer that a user receives as well as a record for when a user actually views the offer. There are also records for when a user completes an offer.

Keep in mind as well that someone using the app might make a purchase through the app without having received an offer or seen an offer.

Example¶

To give an example, a user could receive a discount offer buy 10 dollars get 2 off on Monday. The offer is valid for 10 days from receipt. If the customer accumulates at least 10 dollars in purchases during the validity period, the customer completes the offer.

However, there are a few things to watch out for in this data set. Customers do not opt into the offers that they receive; in other words, a user can receive an offer, never actually view the offer, and still complete the offer. For example, a user might receive the "buy 10 dollars get 2 dollars off offer", but the user never opens the offer during the 10 day validity period. The customer spends 15 dollars during those ten days. There will be an offer completion record in the data set; however, the customer was not influenced by the offer because the customer never viewed the offer.

Cleaning¶

This makes data cleaning especially important and tricky.

You'll also want to take into account that some demographic groups will make purchases even if they don't receive an offer. From a business perspective, if a customer is going to make a 10 dollar purchase without an offer anyway, you wouldn't want to send a buy 10 dollars get 2 dollars off offer. You'll want to try to assess what a certain demographic group will buy when not receiving any offers.

Final Advice¶

Because this is a capstone project, you are free to analyze the data any way you see fit. For example, you could build a machine learning model that predicts how much someone will spend based on demographics and offer type. Or you could build a model that predicts whether or not someone will respond to an offer. Or, you don't need to build a machine learning model at all. You could develop a set of heuristics that determine what offer you should send to each customer (i.e., 75 percent of women customers who were 35 years old responded to offer A vs 40 percent from the same demographic to offer B, so send offer A).

Data Sets¶

The data is contained in three files:

  • portfolio.json - containing offer ids and meta data about each offer (duration, type, etc.)
  • profile.json - demographic data for each customer
  • transcript.json - records for transactions, offers received, offers viewed, and offers completed

Here is the schema and explanation of each variable in the files:

portfolio.json

  • id (string) - offer id
  • offer_type (string) - type of offer ie BOGO, discount, informational
  • difficulty (int) - minimum required spend to complete an offer
  • reward (int) - reward given for completing an offer
  • duration (int) - time for offer to be open, in days
  • channels (list of strings)

profile.json

  • age (int) - age of the customer
  • became_member_on (int) - date when customer created an app account
  • gender (str) - gender of the customer (note some entries contain 'O' for other rather than M or F)
  • id (str) - customer id
  • income (float) - customer's income

transcript.json

  • event (str) - record description (ie transaction, offer received, offer viewed, etc.)
  • person (str) - customer id
  • time (int) - time in hours since start of test. The data begins at time t=0
  • value - (dict of strings) - either an offer id or transaction amount depending on the record

Note: If you are using the workspace, you will need to go to the terminal and run the command conda update pandas before reading in the files. This is because the version of pandas in the workspace cannot read in the transcript.json file correctly, but the newest version of pandas can. transcript = pd.read_json('data/transcript.json', orient='records', lines=True)

we understood from the preface that transcript can carry either the offer_id or the transaction amount we need to use apply to parse the value column to extract offer and amount respectively

In [96]:
#the format of value is key: value pair, so we can utilize the dictionary
#methods to extract relevant values from it

transcript['offer_id']= transcript['value'].apply(lambda x : x.get('offer id',x.get('offer_id', np.nan)))

Important points that we can see here

  • Looking at the age stats we can conclude, most users are middle-aged beteween 42-66 years old.
  • After analyzing the income stats we can conclude that starbucks attracts middle-to-upper-class customers ($50K-$80K income).
  • Majority of users joined between 2016-2017, which would mean starbucsk mostly ran an amazing promotional campaign during this timeframe.
  • Users have been members for an average of 3.5-4 years.
  • What can we infer and strategy that need to focus on based above data?
    • Need to focus on creating personalized offers based on age & income.
    • Loyalty programs is one great strategy to let customers know they are valued, for long-term members.
    • Though we see diverse population, option Starbucks service, young customer populatioin is yet not penetrated and their lies a great scope of adding new cusotmers, need promotions to attract this segment of customers.

import seaborn as sns

plt.figure(figsize=(12,5))
plt.subplot(1,3,1)
sns.histplot(profile['age'], bins=30, kde=True)
plt.title('Age Distribution')

plt.subplot(1,3,2)
sns.histplot(profile['income'], bins=30, kde=True)
plt.title('Income Distribution')

plt.subplot(1,3,3)
sns.histplot(profile['membership_days'], bins=30, kde=True)
plt.title('Customers loyalty check')


            
plt.show()

Wuu Huuu ~~¶

  • Our histplot output justifies what we inferred from our describe() output.
  • Age distribution follows a normal distribution, ranging from age 20 to 80
  • While the income graph is a little right skewed, which confirms that majority of the population is earning berween 50-80k
  • Membership days, show that we have a little left skewed graph, meaning we have new members joining at regular intervals.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

gender_income = profile.set_index('gender').groupby('gender')['income'].mean()
#print(gender_income)
gender_counts = profile['gender'].value_counts().sort_index()
#print(gender_counts)
colors = ['Pink', 'Blue', 'Green', 'Gray']  


plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
plt.bar(x=gender_counts.index, height=gender_income, width=0.4, color=colors[:len(gender_counts)])
plt.xlabel("Gender")
plt.ylabel("Average Income ($)")
plt.title("Gender vs Average Income")
plt.show()

CONCLUSIVE ANSWER BASED ON SCATTER PLOT, BOXPLOT AND BAR GRAPH

  • Income values appear to be spread across different ages, with most data points concentrated between 50k to 80k.
  • There is a strong linear trend of Female & Male gender in their gender group between age and income, income does increase with increase in age. But overall, in terms of avergae income, women are shining like a diamond, more power to them.
  • While younger individuals (~20s) seem to have lower incomes, mid-life (30–70) has a wide variation in incomes.

  • Great amount of transactios, that's good for starbucks, but need to check what kind of transactions, shouldn't be an event that is for discount which might not be good
  • We need to analyze offer viewed vs. completed.

# I am curios how much Revenue did Starbucks generate from ~15k customers
# utilizing dateutil library and extracting relativedelta module to find the
#difference between 2 dates and break it down in years, months, days
In [113]:
from dateutil.relativedelta import relativedelta
import pandas as pd
money_earned=transcript[transcript['amount'] > 0 ]['amount'].sum()
diff= relativedelta(profile['became_member_on'].max(),profile['became_member_on'].min())
print(f"Starbucks revenue from {profile['became_member_on'].min() }, to {profile['became_member_on'].max()} i.e., {diff.years} years,and {diff.days} days is around {round(money_earned)}$")

# Renamnig columns for merging
profile.rename(columns={'id': 'person'}, inplace=True)
portfolio.rename(columns={'id': 'offer_id'}, inplace=True)

data = transcript.merge(profile, on='person', how='left')
data = data.merge(portfolio, on='offer_id', how='left')

data = data.sort_values(['person', 'time'])

data['offer_received'] = (data['event'] == 'offer received').astype(int)
data['offer_viewed'] = (data['event'] == 'offer viewed').astype(int)
data['offer_completed'] = (data['event'] == 'offer completed').astype(int)


#the logic here we are using is groupoing the person, time, offer_id 
# then taking  the count for viewed row in new column
 
data['successful_completion'] = data.groupby(['person', 'offer_id'])['offer_viewed'].cumsum()
data['successful_completion'] = (data['successful_completion'] > 0) & (data['offer_completed'] == 1)

We will now focus on creating on model¶

  • train and test that would help us predict based on customerss : age, income, became_member_on, Offer Type( bogo, discount, informational), Offer Interaction( offer_received, offer_viewed, offer_completed), total money spent( total_spent)
  • and the invvariant/dependetn feature prediction i.e., our Target Variable: successful_completion

STEPS FOR TRAINING A MODEL¶

  • Every model has some basic steps that is followed all the time, we will try to break those steps down and follow along for all models so that way we can increase our speed.

    STEP 1

    • We need to figure out which features are we going to consider.
    • Have to be extra cautious that only the relevant features are being considered, as some random feature might lead to incorrect prediiton
    • Also model work the best on numeric columns, providing columns wiht string will not work the best for Linear data, try to break down all relevant columns in numeric form for the best results.

    STEP 2

    • we need to decide what is our independent/target variable? This will what we will predict from our model and then later compare for accuracy if the model is efficient enough

    STEP 3

    • Break the dataset we choose into train and test part. the best division is usually 80-20, where 80 is the data on which we train our model to learn for predicting the right values and 20% is the data on which we will test whether our model is predicting the right answers.

    STEP 4

    • Deciding which Model to choose. this is tricky and we need to be aware what kind of data do we have, is it: - Linear? - Non- linear? - Complex? requires a lot of feature?
    • considering this we need to implement the right one.

    STEP 5

    • Once the model is decided and initialized with required params, need to fit the model and then predict.

    STEP 6

    • Check for the accuracy score to understand how well our model performed, and then use classification_report model to understand the specifications of the model how it did on different FALSE POSITIVE, TRUE POSITIVE, FALSE NEGATIVE, TRUE NEGATIVE scnearios.

  • if we keep these points in mind, all models the same logic.

We are going to use several models:¶

  • as we have studied so far in our course several models which has helped us to predict models, let's make them all work for us, to get the most accurate preductions

  • We have RandomForestClassifier:: Best for handling missing data, non-linearity, and large datasets, our dataset is not that large, also is almost linear, but it doesn't overfit adn generalizes well so this would be our top coice.

  • other is Logistic Regression → Best for simple, interpretable problems, but when there are several features, it might not be the right choice and here we are considering several features, so need to check the accuracy.

  • Gradient Boosting is one Gradient Descent focussed model→ Best when accuracy is the top priority, which we need here also captures non-linear dependencies but let's see, how all 3 perfomrs to our dataset

Analyzing the above data:¶

  • Firstly Understanding what all terms mean:

Metric _____ Meaning

Accuracy The overall percentage of correctly predicted instances.

Precision Of all predicted positives, how many were actually positive? (TP / (TP + FP))

Recall(Sensitivity) Of all actual positives, how many were correctly predicted? (TP / (TP + FN))

F1-Score Harmonic mean of Precision & Recall (2 × Precision × Recall / (Precision + Recall))

Support The number of actual instances per class.

METRICS? New addition¶

The goal of our Starbucks Capstone Project is to predict whether a customer will respond to a promotional offer. Since we are dealing with a classification problem, selecting the right evaluation metrics is crucial

Challenges in Model Evaluation

  • Customers may receive an offer but not view it.

  • Some users might complete an offer without viewing it.

  • Using just accuracy is not ideal because it does not consider false positives and false negatives. Instead, we will now consider Precision, Recall, and F1-Score to get a holistic evaluation.

BREAKING DOWN METRICS IN DETAIL:¶

  • Key Metrics & thier justification

  1. Accuracy

    • What odes Accuracy mean? When we break it down at formula level:

      • Formula: (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP + FN)
      • TP= True Postive
      • TN= True Negative
      • FP= False Positive
      • FN = False negative

    • From the formula we understand if we have equally balanced outcomes, i.e., true postivie and true negative then we would get accuracy as a better metric but here True negative is dominating i.e., most users are not completing offers.

    SO ACCURACY IS NOT RIGHT METRIC TO USE FOR DECIDING THE MODEL

  2. Precision

    • what do we mean by precision? Breaking it at formula level,

      • Formula: TP / (TP + FP)

    • This metric helps us in measuing how many predicted completions were actually completed.

    • If a model has high precision that would mean we are not sending offers to customers who mostly won't opt for the offers.

  3. Recall

    • what do we mean by recall? Breaking at formula level:

      • TP / (TP + FN)

    • This helps us in capturing, all actual completions. High recall will ensure we are nott missing customers who would have engaged with an offer.

    THIS WOULD BE one of OUR RIGHT METRIC TO CONSIDER

  4. F1-Score

    • what do we mean by F1-Score: Breaking it at Formula level:

      • 2 * (Precision * Recall) / (Precision + Recall)

    • This one is considering recall as one of its attributes, and other is precision, so toether ensures a balance between not sending unnecessary offers and not missing potential users.

PRECISION + RECALL + F1 are our metrics¶

  • let's check all over models based on these:

After going through the result, what did we conclude?¶

  • we understand the overall performance for RECALL + PRECISION + F1 was better than other 2, we will try to optimize hyperparameters like regularization strength, penalty type, and solver for better efficiency.

FINE-TUNING:¶

We had learned GridSearchCV for fine tuning our model

  • let's try to shake fine tune Logistic Regression model

  • Steps to remember while fine tuning :

    STEP1:

    • We need to import GridSearchCV module from sklearn.model_selection library, that's all

    STEP2:

    • which params to choose for fine-tuning? this is the most important one.
    • param_grid is one of the params that takes a dictionary with several key-values in it, we have a whole list to choose from, again to decide the best ones you need to know how the model perfromed and which part of tuning would improve the accurancy.
    • We will consider C (Inverse of regularization strength) → will heop in controling the complexity.
    • penalty → Can be Lasso or Ridge.
    • solver → Choose based on the penalty type. are pretty common ones. We can check below official link for it. https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.model_selection.GridSearchCV.html

    STEP3:

    • intialize the model with required params, and then fit to check how much it increased the accuracy, then look for which were the best hyperparameters, etimators

    STEP4:

    • Predict and check accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score
In [157]:
#regularization is the most important aspect we will start focusing on 
# strenghting the regulatziaition and then as we move ahead see what more change
#will be required 

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression


#Above link has complete details on regualization technique
#Regularization strenght (C) and types of regularizaiton (penalty)
#solver that supports our required techniques
param_grid = {
    'C': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10, 100],  
    'penalty': ['l1', 'l2'],  
    'solver': ['liblinear', 'saga']  
}

#Step1:Intitialziton 

log_reg = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)

#step2: Performoing GridSearchCV
grid_search = GridSearchCV(log_reg, param_grid, scoring='f1', cv=5, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2)
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

#step3 Best hyperparameters
print("Best Parameters:", grid_search.best_params_)

#Step3 best evaluator
best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_
y_pred = best_model.predict(X_test)

# step4 checking our Metrics post 
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score

print("Optimized Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("Optimized Precision:", precision_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("Optimized Recall:", recall_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("Optimized F1-Score:", f1_score(y_test, y_pred))

We got ConvergenceWarning warning?¶

  • meaning our model did not fully converge within the given number of iterations (max_iter=1000).
  • lets' try to see what we can do?
  • remember right hand thumb rule for Logistic Regression, scale the data, normalized data works the best with LR.
  • Regularization might betoo strong, will increae the C value.
  • try with much many iterations
  • use 'solver': 'liblinear' provided by last run.
In [373]:
#fixing the model

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

log_reg = LogisticRegression(max_iter=5000, solver='liblinear')

param_grid = {
    'C': [0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000], 
    'penalty': ['l1', 'l2'],
}

grid_search = GridSearchCV(log_reg, param_grid, scoring='f1', cv=5, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2)
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
print("Best Parameters:", grid_search.best_params_)
best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_
y_pred = best_model.predict(X_test)
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score
print("Optimized Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("Optimized Precision:", precision_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("Optimized Recall:", recall_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("Optimized F1-Score:", f1_score(y_test, y_pred))

We realized here that the model is overfitting, as it predict the offer will be completed only when we provide the offer_completed feature =1¶

  • The approach we had so far, is leading to overfitting, meaning, it has learned a pattern, even after trying to regularize and enhance using gridSearch the model is not good, why?

  • Because it considers the successful completion as linear with Offer completed. There will be no entry where offer_recieved or viewed will have successful_completion as True, hence model is not knowing that offer_recieved is the starting phase which will ultimately lead to completed.

  • Now We must to do 2 things:

     - Change the dataFrame, so the offer_received + viewed + completed pairs are clubbed together into 1, by which model based on other features will learn that offer_recieved --> completed.

 - We will stick to XGB classifier only, as we would need to do a lot of Regularization to imporve the models Metrics and can target one model.

 - Let's start with customizing our DF
In [379]:
def preprocess_data(transcript):
    
    agg_data = transcript.groupby(['person', 'offer_id']).agg({
        'offer_received': 'max',  
        'offer_viewed': 'max',  
        'offer_completed': 'max', 
        'time': ['min', 'max'],  
        'reward': 'sum'  
    }).reset_index()

    agg_data.columns = ['person', 'offer_id', 'offer_received', 'offer_viewed', 'offer_completed',
                        'time_received', 'time_completed', 'total_reward']

    agg_data['time_to_complete'] = agg_data['time_completed'] - agg_data['time_received']
    agg_data['time_to_complete'].fillna(-1, inplace=True)  

    return agg_data


agg_transcript = preprocess_data(transcript)

import pandas as pd

promo_status = pd.DataFrame([{
    'TOT_RCV': agg_transcript[agg_transcript['offer_received'] == 1].shape[0],
    'TOT_VIEW': agg_transcript[agg_transcript['offer_viewed'] == 1].shape[0],
    'TOT_COMP': agg_transcript[agg_transcript['offer_completed'] == 1].shape[0],
    'TOT_RCV_VW_NOT_COMP': agg_transcript[(agg_transcript['offer_received'] == 1) & 
                                          (agg_transcript['offer_viewed'] == 1) & 
                                          (agg_transcript['offer_completed'] != 1)].shape[0],
    'TOT_RCV_VW_COMP': agg_transcript[(agg_transcript['offer_received'] == 1) & 
                                      (agg_transcript['offer_viewed'] == 1) & 
                                      (agg_transcript['offer_completed'] == 1)].shape[0],
    'TOT_ONLY_RCV': agg_transcript[(agg_transcript['offer_received'] == 1) & 
                                   (agg_transcript['offer_viewed'] != 1) & 
                                   (agg_transcript['offer_completed'] != 1)].shape[0],
    'TOT_RCV_COMP_ONLY': agg_transcript[(agg_transcript['offer_received'] == 1) & 
                                        (agg_transcript['offer_viewed'] != 1) & 
                                        (agg_transcript['offer_completed'] == 1)].shape[0]
}])

promo_status=pd.DataFrame(promo_status.stack(), columns=['count']).reset_index().rename(columns={'index': 'offer_status'})

This MODEL is stil a overfitting, why?¶

  • Still considers when offer_viewed is 1 but for recieved it gives rarely 1, meaning it still considers that offer_viewed is the most impotatn feautre for prediction.
  • we need to increase the Recall value & Precission by Hyperparameter Optimization → will tyr to tune most important and common HP n_estimators, max_depth, learning_rate
In [417]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.2],
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 7]
}

grid_search = GridSearchCV(XGBClassifier(random_state=42), param_grid, cv=3, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=-1, verbose=2)
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Best Parameters:", grid_search.best_params_)
print("Best Accuracy:", grid_search.best_score_)

DON'T SEE MUCH IMPROVEMENT:¶

  • it is still over-fitting, how? Shows our prediction works fine when we provide offer_viewed = 1 but rarely shows preictionr=1 when offer_received is provided as 1.

  • this is mostly because our dataset isn't big enough now, why do i say so?

  • Because now agg_data has merged rows, which is ~63k rows with combination of:

    • offer_recieved
    • offer_received + offer_viewed
    • offer_received + offer_viewed + offer_completed
    • offer_received + offer_completed

  • We would focus on REGULARIZATION~~

REGULARIZATION - Controlling Overfitting¶

  • Regularization is a technique used in machine learning to prevent overfitting by penalizing complex models. It helps ensure that the model generalizes well to unseen data rather than just memorizing the training data.

    • Currently our model is memorizing the true patterns but also the noise in the training data. This is making our model perform well on training data but poorly on unseen data.

    • Regularization adds a penalty term to the model's loss function, forcing it to learn simpler patterns.

    • 2major Regularization that we had for Logistic Regression:

      • L1 Regularization (Lasso Regression - L1 Penalty)
      • L2 Regularization (Ridge Regression - L2 Penalty)

    • In XGBoost, we have:

      • L1 Regularization (reg_alpha) → Helps with feature selection.
      • L2 Regularization (reg_lambda) → Helps reduce overfitting without removing features.

  • On top of the L1 & L2, we have utilized below to have the best ever model we can get:

    • min_child_weight
    • gamma
    • subsample
    • colsample_bytree
    • scale_pos_weight
In [360]:
param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300],
    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.2],
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 7],
    'min_child_weight': [1, 3, 5],
    'gamma': [0, 0.1, 0.3, 0.5],
    'subsample': [0.5, 0.7, 1.0],
    'colsample_bytree': [0.3, 0.6, 0.8, 1.0],
    'reg_alpha': [0, 0.1, 0.5, 1.0],
    'reg_lambda': [0.5, 1.0, 1.5, 2.0],
    'scale_pos_weight': [1, 2, 5, 10]
}


grid_search = GridSearchCV(XGBClassifier(random_state=42), param_grid, cv=5, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=-1, verbose=2)
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Best Parameters:", grid_search.best_params_)
print("Best Accuracy:", grid_search.best_score_)

  age_offer_stats = agg_transcript.groupby('age_group')[['offer_received', 'offer_viewed', 'offer_completed']].sum()

Conclusiion & Recommendations:¶

Gender-Based Engagement

* Males received more offers overall compared to females.
* The percentage of offer completions remains high across genders, indicating that both groups are likely to act on promotions.
* However, a notable portion of received offers are not viewed, suggesting that engagement strategies (like personalized recommendations) could be improved.

Age-Based Engagement

* Older age groups (45-60, 60+) exhibit higher engagement rates in all stages: receiving, viewing, and completing offers.
* Younger age groups (18-30, 30-45) show lower offer completion rates despite receiving a significant number of offers.
* This indicates that younger customers may need different types of incentives or communication channels to drive engagement.

Recommendations¶

Targeted Promotions for Younger Customers

* Since younger users tend to receive offers but not complete them, Starbucks should explore:
    - More engaging formats, mostly over Social media campaigns to reinforce the value of offers.

`Middled-Age + older customer``

- Since older customers show high offer completion rates, more BOGO and discount offers should be targeted toward them.

ALERT~~~~~~¶

  • A significant number of offers are received but not viewed. Starbucks should:
  • Implement in-app reminders.
  • Use email campaigns with personalized content based on previous offer interactions.
